{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DQdcoi9P3rELwXoPGeJ55U","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_014bEDUpbc1sTEETCKKE74eC","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"kubectl -n elasticsearch create configmap config-audit --from-literal=findings.txt=\"$(cat <<'FINDINGS'\nELASTICSEARCH CLUSTER SECURITY & OPERATIONAL COMPLIANCE AUDIT\nDate: 2026-06-26\nCluster: es-cluster (3-node, Elasticsearch 8.11.1)\nNamespace: elasticsearch\nAuditor: automated read-only audit\n\n====================================================================\nSUMMARY\n====================================================================\nCRITICAL: 3 findings | HIGH: 3 findings | MEDIUM: 3 findings | INFO: 4 findings\n\n====================================================================\nCRITICAL FINDINGS\n====================================================================\n\n[CRIT-1] AUTHENTICATION DISABLED (xpack.security.enabled: false)\nSource: ConfigMap es-config / Node settings (all 3 nodes confirmed)\nDetail: X-Pack security is explicitly disabled cluster-wide. No\n  authentication is required to access the Elasticsearch API. Any\n  network client with reach to port 9200 or 9300 can read all data,\n  modify all indices, change cluster settings, and delete indices\n  without supplying any credentials. The audit API itself was fully\n  accessible anonymously.\nCIS Benchmark: ES 8.x CIS v1.0 §6.1 - Enable authentication\nRemediation (do NOT apply during audit): Set xpack.security.enabled: true\n  and configure built-in user passwords (elasticsearch-reset-password).\n\n[CRIT-2] TLS DISABLED ON HTTP API (xpack.security.http.ssl.enabled: false)\nSource: ConfigMap es-config / Node settings confirmed on all 3 nodes\nDetail: All HTTP traffic on port 9200 is transmitted in plaintext.\n  Credentials (when authentication is eventually enabled), queries,\n  and responses — including any sensitive document content — are\n  visible to any network observer on the pod network.\nRemediation: Enable SSL, generate or provide a signed certificate,\n  and set xpack.security.http.ssl.certificate/key paths.\n\n[CRIT-3] TLS DISABLED ON INTER-NODE TRANSPORT (xpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled: false)\nSource: ConfigMap es-config / Node settings confirmed on all 3 nodes\nDetail: Internal cluster communication on port 9300 (shard replication,\n  cluster state sync, node-to-node queries) is plaintext. A compromised\n  pod in the cluster can intercept intra-cluster data replication or\n  inject cluster-state messages.\nRemediation: Enable transport TLS and supply a CA-signed or self-signed\n  certificate bundle to all nodes.\n\n====================================================================\nHIGH FINDINGS\n====================================================================\n\n[HIGH-1] NO NETWORK POLICIES — UNRESTRICTED INTRA-CLUSTER ACCESS\nSource: kubectl -n elasticsearch get networkpolicy -> No resources found\nDetail: No Kubernetes NetworkPolicy exists in the elasticsearch namespace.\n  Any pod in any namespace in the cluster can reach port 9200 (HTTP API)\n  and port 9300 (transport). Combined with disabled authentication (CRIT-1),\n  any workload in the cluster has full administrative access to the data.\nRemediation: Apply NetworkPolicies to restrict ingress to port 9200 to\n  only authorized namespaces/pods, and restrict port 9300 to only the\n  es-cluster pods themselves.\n\n[HIGH-2] NO POD SECURITY CONTEXT SET\nSource: StatefulSet es-cluster .spec.template.spec.securityContext = {}\n  Container elasticsearch: no securityContext defined\nDetail: Pods run with Kubernetes default security settings — no\n  runAsNonRoot enforcement, no readOnlyRootFilesystem, no\n  allowPrivilegeEscalation: false, no seccomp profile, no capability\n  drop. The Elasticsearch process may run as root inside the container.\nRemediation: Add a container-level securityContext with:\n  allowPrivilegeEscalation: false, readOnlyRootFilesystem: false (ES\n  needs writes to /data and /logs), runAsNonRoot: true, runAsUser: 1000\n  (the elasticsearch user in the official image), and drop ALL capabilities.\n\n[HIGH-3] NETWORK BINDING ON ALL INTERFACES (network.host: 0.0.0.0)\nSource: ConfigMap es-config / verified in node settings\nDetail: Elasticsearch listens on 0.0.0.0 for both HTTP (9200) and\n  transport (9300), binding to every network interface on the pod. While\n  access is gated by Kubernetes network rules, a more restrictive binding\n  (to the pod IP only) limits exposure in case of host-network privilege\n  escalation. This amplifies the risk of CRIT-1/CRIT-2/CRIT-3.\nRemediation: Set network.host to the pod IP via field ref injection\n  (e.g., _site_ or ${POD_IP} field ref), and configure separate\n  http.host / transport.host if needed.\n\n====================================================================\nMEDIUM FINDINGS\n====================================================================\n\n[MED-1] NO DEDICATED MASTER NODES — ALL NODES ARE MASTER-ELIGIBLE DATA/INGEST\nSource: Node roles: [master, data, ingest] on all 3 nodes\nDetail: Every node is simultaneously eligible for master election, runs\n  data shards, and processes ingest pipelines. Under heavy indexing or\n  query load the master process can be starved, increasing the risk of\n  master-election instability and false split-brain detection. For a\n  production cluster with sensitive data, dedicated master nodes are\n  recommended.\nRecommendation: For 3-node clusters this is an accepted tradeoff; for\n  5+ node clusters split into dedicated masters (no data/ingest roles).\n\n[MED-2] EMPTY PERSISTENT AND TRANSIENT CLUSTER SETTINGS\nSource: GET /_cluster/settings?flat_settings=true -> persistent:{} transient:{}\nDetail: No explicit cluster-level security or operational settings have\n  been persisted (e.g., no action.destructive_requires_name, no\n  cluster.max_shards_per_node cap). With security disabled, any anonymous\n  caller can issue DELETE /*. At minimum, destructive_requires_name should\n  be enabled to prevent accidental index wildcard deletion.\nRemediation: PUT /_cluster/settings with\n  \"persistent\":{\"action.destructive_requires_name\": true}.\n\n[MED-3] INDEX shard routing requires tier=hot — OPERATIONAL AVAILABILITY RISK\nSource: GET /_all/_settings -> routing.allocation.require.tier: hot\n  and routing.allocation.include._tier_preference: data_content\nDetail: The audit-index has a hard allocation requirement (require.tier=hot).\n  All 3 nodes carry the node.attr.tier=hot attribute, so shards currently\n  allocate. However, if any node is reconfigured without this attribute\n  (e.g., during a tier migration), its primary or replica shards will go\n  unassigned and the index will become partially unavailable. There is\n  no fallback tier configured.\nRecommendation: Document the tier-routing requirement and ensure any\n  infrastructure change to node attributes is coordinated with index\n  allocation awareness settings.\n\n====================================================================\nINFORMATIONAL FINDINGS\n====================================================================\n\n[INFO-1] ELASTICSEARCH VERSION 8.11.1 — NOT LATEST 8.x PATCH\nDetail: Running 8.11.1 (built 2023-11-11). Later 8.x releases include\n  security patches. Verify against current Elastic security advisories\n  and plan an upgrade path.\n\n[INFO-2] LOG4J MITIGATION FLAG PRESENT\nDetail: JVM argument -Dlog4j2.formatMsgNoLookups=true is set on all nodes.\n  ES 8.x ships a patched Log4j (CVE-2021-44228 not applicable), but the\n  flag provides defence-in-depth. No action required.\n\n[INFO-3] MMAP DISABLED (node.store.allow_mmap: false)\nDetail: Using NIO instead of mmap for Lucene index files. This is the\n  recommended setting for Kubernetes deployments (avoids requiring\n  vm.max_map_count kernel parameter on the host). No security concern.\n\n[INFO-4] CPU THROTTLING OBSERVED — RESOURCE PRESSURE\nDetail: cgroup CPU stats show significant throttling on all nodes:\n  ~22-23% of CPU scheduling periods result in throttling. This indicates\n  the 1-CPU limit may be undersized for the current workload. Under load,\n  master election heartbeats could be delayed, risking false master\n  failovers. Not a security issue but a reliability concern.\n\n====================================================================\nCLUSTER INVENTORY\n====================================================================\nNodes:        3 (es-cluster-0, es-cluster-1, es-cluster-2)\nRoles/node:   master, data, ingest (no role separation)\nES Version:   8.11.1\nHeap/node:    512 MB (Xms=Xmx=512m; node-0 at 61% heap usage)\nSwap:         disabled on all nodes (correct)\nIndices:      1 (audit-index: 3 primary shards, 1 replica, 0 documents)\nCluster UUID: k37YY0uDR2KrBpXnKSjkiA\nCluster Status: GREEN\nServices:     es-http (ClusterIP:9200), es-cluster headless (9300)\nSecrets:      NONE (consistent with authentication being disabled)\nNetworkPolicies: NONE\nPod securityContext: NONE set\n\n====================================================================\nAUDIT METHODOLOGY\n====================================================================\nAll data collected via read-only kubectl and curl commands.\nNo cluster settings, indices, or resources were modified.\nAPIs queried: /_cluster/settings, /_all/_settings, /_cluster/health,\n  /_nodes (settings, stats), /_cat/indices, /_cat/nodes,\n  kubectl get pods/statefulset/svc/secret/networkpolicy/configmap.\nFINDINGS\"\n)\" 2>&1","description":"Create config-audit ConfigMap with security audit findings"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":862,"cache_read_input_tokens":41261,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":862},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not