te or provide a signed certificate,\n  and set xpack.security.http.ssl.certificate/key paths.\n\n[CRIT-3] TLS DISABLED ON INTER-NODE TRANSPORT (xpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled: false)\nSource: ConfigMap es-config / Node settings confirmed on all 3 nodes\nDetail: Internal cluster communication on port 9300 (shard replication,\n  cluster state sync, node-to-node queries) is plaintext. A compromised\n  pod in the cluster can intercept intra-cluster data replication or\n  inject cluster-state messages.\nRemediation: Enable transport TLS and supply a CA-signed or self-signed\n  certificate bundle to all nodes.\n\n====================================================================\nHIGH FINDINGS\n====================================================================\n\n[HIGH-1] NO NETWORK POLICIES - UNRESTRICTED INTRA-CLUSTER ACCESS\nSource: kubectl -n elasticsearch get networkpolicy -> No resources found\nDetail: No Kubernetes NetworkPolicy exists in the elasticsearch namespace.\n  Any pod in any namespace in the cluster can reach port 9200 (HTTP API)\n  and port 9300 (transport). Combined with disabled authentication\n  (CRIT-1), any workload in the cluster has full administrative access\n  to the data.\nRemediation: Apply NetworkPolicies to restrict ingress to port 9200 to\n  only authorized namespaces/pods, and restrict port 9300 to only the\n  es-cluster pods themselves.\n\n[HIGH-2] NO POD SECURITY CONTEXT SET\nSource: StatefulSet es-cluster .spec.template.spec.securityContext = {}\n  Container elasticsearch: no securityContext defined\nDetail: Pods run with Kubernetes default security settings. No\n  runAsNonRoot enforcement, no readOnlyRootFilesystem, no\n  allowPrivilegeEscalation: false, no seccomp profile, no capability\n  drop. The Elasticsearch process may run as root inside the container.\nRemediation: Add a container-level securityContext with:\n  allowPrivilegeEscalation: false, runAsNonRoot: true, runAsUser: 1000\n  (the elasticsearch user in the official image), and drop ALL\n  Linux capabilities.\n\n[HIGH-3] NETWORK BINDING ON ALL INTERFACES (network.host: 0.0.0.0)\nSource: ConfigMap es-config / verified in node settings across all nodes\nDetail: Elasticsearch listens on 0.0.0.0 for both HTTP (9200) and\n  transport (9300), binding to every network interface on the pod.\n  While access is gated by Kubernetes network rules, a more restrictive\n  binding (to the pod IP only) limits exposure in case of host-network\n  privilege escalation. This amplifies the risk of CRIT-1/CRIT-2/CRIT-3.\nRemediation: Set network.host to the pod IP via field ref injection\n  (use _site_ or a POD_IP env var from fieldRef), and configure\n  http.host/transport.host separately if needed.\n\n====================================================================\nMEDIUM FINDINGS\n====================================================================\n\n[MED-1] NO DEDICATED MASTER NODES - ALL NODES ARE MASTER+DATA+INGEST\nSource: Node roles on all 3 nodes: [master, data, ingest]\nDetail: Every node is simultaneously master-eligible, runs data shards,\n  and processes ingest pipelines. Under heavy indexing or query load\n  the master process can be starved, increasing risk of master-election\n  instability. For a 3-node cluster this is an accepted tradeoff but\n  should be documented. For 5+ node clusters, dedicated masters are\n  recommended.\n\n[MED-2] NO DESTRUCTIVE ACTION PROTECTION ON CLUSTER SETTINGS\nSource: GET /_cluster/settings -> persistent:{} transient:{}\nDetail: No explicit hardening settings are persisted. Notably,\n  action.destructive_requires_name is not set. With authentication\n  disabled (CRIT-1), any anonymous caller can issue DELETE /* and\n  remove all indices. No shard limit (cluster.max_shards_per_node)\n  is configured either.\nRemediation: After enabling security (CRIT-1), persist:\n  action.destructive_requires_name: true via PUT /_cluster/settings.\n\n[MED-3] HARD SHARD ALLOCATION ROUTING REQUIREMENT ON audit-index\nSource: GET /_all/_settings\n  routing.allocation.require.tier: hot\n  routing.allocation.include._tier_preference: data_content\nDetail: The audit-index has a hard require filter for tier=hot. All\n  current nodes carry node.attr.tier=hot so shards are allocated now.\n  If any node loses this attribute during reconfiguration or a\n  tier migration, its shards will become unassigned and the index\n  will partially lose availability. No fallback tier is configured.\nRecommendation: Document the tier-routing requirement and coordinate\n  any node attribute changes with index allocation settings.\n\n====================================================================\nINFORMATIONAL FINDINGS\n====================================================================\n\n[INFO-1] ELASTICSEARCH VERSION 8.11.1 - NOT LATEST 8.x PATCH\nDetail: Running 8.11.1 (built 2023-11-11). Later 8.x patch releases\n  include security fixes. Verify against current Elastic security\n  advisories and plan an upgrade to the latest 8.x release.\n\n[INFO-2] LOG4J MITIGATION FLAG PRESENT\nDetail: JVM argument -Dlog4j2.formatMsgNoLookups=true is set on all\n  nodes. ES 8.x ships a patched Log4j (CVE-2021-44228 is not\n  applicable to ES 8.x), but the flag provides defence-in-depth.\n  No action required.\n\n[INFO-3] MMAP DISABLED (node.store.allow_mmap: false)\nDetail: NIO is used instead of mmap for Lucene index files. This is\n  the recommended Kubernetes deployment setting (avoids requiring the\n  vm.max_map_count kernel parameter on the host node). No security\n  concern; this is correct configuration.\n\n[INFO-4] CPU THROTTLING OBSERVED - RESOURCE PRESSURE\nDetail: cgroup CPU stats show significant throttling on all nodes\n  (~22-23% of scheduling periods throttled). The 1-CPU limit may be\n  undersized for current workload. Under sustained load, master\n  election heartbeats could be delayed, risking false master failovers.\n  Not a security issue but a reliability/availability concern.\n\n